        <h1>Neil Armstrong</h1>
        <img src="/images/neil-armstrong.jpeg" alt="Neil Armstrong" class="image-fixed-size">
        <p>Neil Armstrong was an American astronaut and aeronautical engineer who became the first person to walk on the Moon on July 20, 1969, during the Apollo 11 mission. His first words upon stepping on the Moon's surface, "That's one small step for man, one giant leap for mankind," have been etched in history.</p>
        <p>Before becoming an astronaut, Armstrong was an officer in the U.S. Navy and served in the Korean War. Later, he joined the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics (NACA), which transitioned into NASA. Armstrong's contributions to the field of aerospace and his historic lunar landing have made him a symbol of exploration and human achievement.</p>
        <p>Aside from his iconic lunar walk, Armstrong was also known for his humility and dedication to advancing space exploration. His legacy continues to inspire generations of scientists, engineers, and astronauts.</p>

        <h2>Key Milestones</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>1955 - Earned a degree in Aeronautical Engineering from Purdue University</li>
            <li>1962 - Selected as NASA astronaut</li>
            <li>1966 - Commanded the Gemini 8 mission, his first spaceflight</li>
            <li>1969 - Commanded Apollo 11, the first manned lunar landing</li>
        </ul>
